<!--
========================================================================
FILE: Cart.view.xml — Shopping Cart Page
NAMESPACE: com.shopeasy.app.view
========================================================================

[BEGINNER] WHAT IS THIS VIEW?
The shopping cart page shows all items the user has added. It features:
  1. An empty state with IllustratedMessage when the cart is empty
  2. A list of cart items with images, names, prices, and quantities
  3. A footer with total price and "Proceed to Checkout" button

[INTERMEDIATE] KEY CONCEPTS DEMONSTRATED:
  - Expression binding for conditional visibility
  - Binding to a NAMED model (cart>)
  - CustomListItem for fully custom list item layouts
  - HBox/VBox for flexible layouts within list items
  - IllustratedMessage for empty states
  - Footer Toolbar with dynamic content

[ADVANCED] WORKING WITH THE CART JSONModel
The cart model is a JSONModel declared in manifest.json with structure:
  {
    items: [
      { productId: "P001", name: "Mouse", price: 29.99, quantity: 2, imageUrl: "..." },
      { productId: "P002", name: "Keyboard", price: 79.99, quantity: 1, imageUrl: "..." }
    ],
    totalPrice: 139.97,
    itemCount: 3,
    currency: "USD"
  }

All bindings in this view use the "cart>" prefix to read from
this named model instead of the default OData model.

Learn more: docs/03-data-binding.md, docs/04-models.md
========================================================================
-->

<mvc:View
    controllerName="com.shopeasy.app.controller.Cart"
    xmlns="sap.m"
    xmlns:mvc="sap.ui.core.mvc"
    xmlns:core="sap.ui.core"
>
    <Page
        id="cartPage"
        title="{i18n>cartTitle}"
        showNavButton="true"
        navButtonPress=".onNavBack"
    >
        <!--
        [INTERMEDIATE] CONDITIONAL VISIBILITY WITH EXPRESSION BINDING
        ====================================================
        We show TWO different sections based on whether the cart has items:
          1. Empty state (IllustratedMessage) → visible when itemCount === 0
          2. Cart content (List) → visible when itemCount > 0

        This is achieved with EXPRESSION BINDING on the "visible" property.

        visible="{= ${cart>/itemCount} === 0}"
          Breaking it down:
            {= ... }              → Expression binding delimiters
            ${cart>/itemCount}     → Read "itemCount" from the "cart" model
                                     The $ prefix is required inside expressions
            === 0                  → JavaScript strict equality comparison

          When itemCount is 0: expression evaluates to true → visible
          When itemCount is 3: expression evaluates to false → hidden

        [ADVANCED] EXPRESSION BINDING vs. FORMATTER FOR VISIBILITY
        For simple boolean conditions like "is it zero?", expression
        binding is ideal — it's concise and readable inline.

        For complex conditions (like "show if user is admin AND stock > 0
        AND sale is active"), use a formatter function — it's easier to
        debug and test.

        [GOTCHA] When a control is visible="false", it's still in the DOM
        but hidden with display:none. The bindings are still ACTIVE.
        For performance with heavy content, consider using the
        "visible" binding on a parent container, or lazy-load content
        only when it becomes visible.

        [BEST PRACTICE] EMPTY STATES
        Always provide an empty state message. A blank page makes users
        think the app is broken. Good empty states:
          1. Explain WHY it's empty ("Your cart is empty")
          2. Suggest WHAT to do ("Start shopping to add items")
          3. Provide a CTA button ("Continue Shopping")
        -->

        <!-- ===== EMPTY CART STATE ===== -->
        <VBox
            visible="{= ${cart>/itemCount} === 0}"
            alignItems="Center"
            justifyContent="Center"
            class="sapUiMediumMargin"
        >
            <!--
            [BEGINNER] THE <IllustratedMessage> CONTROL — Empty State
            ====================================================
            sap.m.IllustratedMessage displays a professional SVG
            illustration with a title and description. It's the
            SAP Fiori standard for empty, error, and success states.

            illustrationType="sapIllus-EmptyList"
              [INTERMEDIATE] SAP provides many built-in illustration types:
                - sapIllus-EmptyList          → Empty list/collection
                - sapIllus-NoSearchResults    → Search returned nothing
                - sapIllus-NoData             → No data available
                - sapIllus-ErrorScreen        → Something went wrong
                - sapIllus-SuccessScreen      → Operation succeeded
                - sapIllus-SimpleBalloon      → General informational
                - sapIllus-Tent              → Under construction
                - sapIllus-NoMail           → No messages

              These illustrations follow SAP's visual language and
              automatically adapt to the current theme (Horizon, Quartz).

            title="{i18n>emptyCart}"
              Main heading: "Your cart is empty"

            description="{i18n>emptyCartMessage}"
              Supporting text: "Start shopping to add items to your cart"

            [BEST PRACTICE] The illustration, title, description, and
            CTA button together form a complete "empty state pattern":
              🖼  [Illustration]      ← Visual empathy
              📝  Your cart is empty  ← What happened
              💬  Start shopping...   ← What to do
              🔘  [Continue Shopping] ← Action to take
            -->
            <IllustratedMessage
                illustrationType="sapIllus-EmptyList"
                title="{i18n>emptyCart}"
                description="{i18n>emptyCartMessage}"
            >
                <additionalContent>
                    <!--
                    [BEGINNER] CTA BUTTON TO CONTINUE SHOPPING
                    ====================================================
                    press=".onContinueShopping"
                      Navigates back to the Home page so the user can
                      browse categories and add products.

                    type="Emphasized"
                      Primary action button styling. This is the only
                      emphasized button on the empty state, guiding the
                      user's eye to the most important action.
                    -->
                    <Button
                        text="{i18n>continueShopping}"
                        type="Emphasized"
                        press=".onContinueShopping"
                    />
                </additionalContent>
            </IllustratedMessage>
        </VBox>

        <!-- ===== CART ITEMS LIST ===== -->
        <!--
        [INTERMEDIATE] CART LIST — VISIBLE ONLY WHEN ITEMS EXIST
        ====================================================
        visible="{= ${cart>/itemCount} > 0}"
          The opposite of the empty state visibility. When there ARE
          items, this list shows and the empty state hides.

          [ADVANCED] An alternative approach is to use a single container
          with a content switch, but the dual-visibility approach is
          simpler and more readable in XML views.

        items="{cart>/items}"
          [BEGINNER] BINDING TO A NAMED MODEL
          This is aggregation binding on the CART model (not the default
          OData model). The "cart>" prefix tells UI5 to use the model
          named "cart":
            - cart>   → Model name prefix (the JSONModel from manifest.json)
            - /items  → Path within that model (the items array)

          Compare with the ProductList binding:
            items="{/Products}"     → Default (unnamed) OData model
            items="{cart>/items}"   → Named "cart" JSONModel

          For each object in the items array, UI5 creates one
          CustomListItem using the template below.

        [INTERMEDIATE] List WITH CustomListItem
        Unlike ObjectListItem (used in ProductList) which has predefined
        layout slots, CustomListItem lets you build the ENTIRE layout
        from scratch using any UI5 controls.

        Use CustomListItem when:
          - The predefined list item types don't match your design
          - You need complex layouts (multiple rows, images, nested controls)
          - You need full control over positioning

        Use ObjectListItem when:
          - Your data fits the object pattern (title, number, attributes)
          - You want consistency with other SAP apps
          - You want responsive layout handled automatically
        -->
        <List
            id="cartList"
            visible="{= ${cart>/itemCount} > 0}"
            items="{cart>/items}"
            noDataText="{i18n>emptyCart}"
            headerText="{i18n>cartTitle}"
        >
            <!--
            [INTERMEDIATE] THE <CustomListItem> CONTROL
            ====================================================
            sap.m.CustomListItem is a blank-canvas list item. You
            fill it with whatever controls you want, giving you
            complete layout freedom.

            type="Inactive"
              [BEGINNER] Since cart items aren't navigational (they
              don't lead to a detail page from the cart), we use
              "Inactive" type. No press highlight, no chevron.

            [ADVANCED] CUSTOM LIST ITEM LIFECYCLE
            Each CustomListItem instance is managed by the List's
            binding. When an item is added to cart>/items, a new
            CustomListItem is created from this template. When an
            item is removed, the corresponding CustomListItem is
            destroyed. The List handles all of this automatically.
            -->
            <CustomListItem type="Inactive">
                <!--
                [BEGINNER] <HBox> — Horizontal Layout
                ====================================================
                sap.m.HBox arranges children horizontally (side by side).
                It's the UI5 equivalent of CSS flex-direction: row.

                Layout structure of each cart item:
                ┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
                │ [Image]  [Name & Price column]  [Qty] [Delete]  │
                └──────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

                alignItems="Center"
                  Vertically centers all children on their midlines.
                  Without this, taller elements (image) and shorter
                  elements (text) would align to the top.

                class="sapUiSmallMargin"
                  Adds consistent spacing around the HBox.

                width="100%"
                  Ensures the HBox stretches to fill the list item width.
                -->
                <HBox
                    alignItems="Center"
                    class="sapUiSmallMargin"
                    width="100%"
                >
                    <!--
                    [INTERMEDIATE] THE <Image> CONTROL — Product Thumbnail
                    ====================================================
                    sap.m.Image renders an <img> element with additional
                    UI5 features like density-aware image switching and
                    decorative mode for accessibility.

                    src="{cart>imageUrl}"
                      The image URL from the cart item data. Note the
                      "cart>" prefix — we're still in the cart model context.

                    width="4rem" / height="4rem"
                      Fixed dimensions for the thumbnail. Using rem units
                      ensures the size scales with the user's font size
                      settings (accessibility benefit).

                    decorative="true"
                      [ADVANCED] ACCESSIBILITY: When true, the image is
                      treated as decorative (not informational). Screen
                      readers will skip it. Use decorative="true" when
                      the image doesn't convey information beyond what's
                      already in the text (product name). Set to false
                      and add alt text for informational images.

                    class="sapUiSmallMarginEnd"
                      Adds margin on the END side (right in LTR, left in RTL).
                      Using "End" instead of "Right" supports RTL languages.
                    -->
                    <Image
                        src="{cart>imageUrl}"
                        width="4rem"
                        height="4rem"
                        decorative="true"
                        class="sapUiSmallMarginEnd"
                    />

                    <!--
                    [BEGINNER] <VBox> FOR PRODUCT NAME AND PRICE
                    ====================================================
                    Nesting a VBox inside the HBox creates a two-line
                    text block: product name on top, price below.

                    Layout:
                    ┌─────────────────────┐
                    │ Wireless Mouse      │  ← Title (Name)
                    │ $29.99              │  ← Text (Price)
                    └─────────────────────┘

                    [INTERMEDIATE] FLEXBOX GROW
                    The VBox has no explicit width, so it will shrink-wrap
                    its content. The ToolbarSpacer-like behavior comes from
                    the HBox's flex layout — the VBox takes available space
                    between the image and the action controls.
                    -->
                    <VBox class="sapUiSmallMarginEnd">
                        <!--
                        [BEGINNER] RELATIVE BINDINGS TO CART MODEL
                        These bindings use "cart>" prefix with relative paths.
                        Since we're inside items="{cart>/items}", each
                        CustomListItem gets a context like "cart>/items/0".
                        So {cart>name} resolves to "cart>/items/0/name"
                        for the first item.
                        -->
                        <Title text="{cart>name}" level="H4" />

                        <Text
                            text="{
                                path: 'cart>price',
                                formatter: '.formatter.formatPrice'
                            }"
                        />
                    </VBox>

                    <!--
                    [INTERMEDIATE] ToolbarSpacer IN A NON-TOOLBAR CONTEXT
                    ====================================================
                    ToolbarSpacer only works inside Toolbar/OverflowToolbar.
                    For FlexBox/HBox spacing, we use a FlexBox with
                    renderType="Bare" and layoutData, or simply use
                    CSS margins. Here, we rely on the natural flex layout
                    and margin classes to space items.
                    -->

                    <!--
                    [BEGINNER] QUANTITY DISPLAY
                    ====================================================
                    A simple Text control showing the quantity, wrapped
                    in an ObjectNumber for a more semantic display with
                    a label.
                    -->
                    <ObjectNumber
                        number="{cart>quantity}"
                        unit="{i18n>quantity}"
                        class="sapUiSmallMarginEnd"
                    />

                    <!--
                    [BEGINNER] DELETE BUTTON — Remove Item from Cart
                    ====================================================
                    icon="sap-icon://decline"
                      The "X" icon, standard for delete/remove actions.

                    type="Reject"
                      [INTERMEDIATE] Red-tinted button styling that
                      signals a destructive action (removing an item).
                      This visual cue helps prevent accidental deletions.

                    press=".onDeleteItem"
                      [INTERMEDIATE] The controller's delete handler:
                        1. Gets the binding context of the pressed button
                        2. Finds the index of the item in the cart array
                        3. Removes it from the cart model
                        4. Recalculates totalPrice and itemCount
                        5. Shows a MessageToast confirmation

                    [ADVANCED] IDENTIFYING WHICH ITEM TO DELETE
                    In the controller, the event source (button) has a
                    binding context that tells us which item it belongs to:

                      onDeleteItem: function(oEvent) {
                        var oCtx = oEvent.getSource().getBindingContext("cart");
                        var sPath = oCtx.getPath();  // e.g., "/items/2"
                        var iIndex = parseInt(sPath.split("/").pop());
                        // Remove item at index from the cart model
                      }
                    -->
                    <Button
                        icon="sap-icon://decline"
                        type="Reject"
                        press=".onDeleteItem"
                        tooltip="{i18n>removeFromCart}"
                    />
                </HBox>
            </CustomListItem>
        </List>

        <!--
        [BEGINNER] PAGE FOOTER — Total Price and Checkout Button
        ====================================================
        The footer bar stays fixed at the bottom of the page. It shows:
          - Total price of all cart items
          - "Proceed to Checkout" button

        visible="{= ${cart>/itemCount} > 0}"
          Only show the footer when there are items in the cart.
          When the cart is empty, the footer hides — the user sees
          only the IllustratedMessage empty state.

        [INTERMEDIATE] FOOTER TOOLBAR LAYOUT
        Using ToolbarSpacer pushes the checkout button to the right:
          [  Total: $127.50          [Proceed to Checkout]  ]
        -->
        <footer>
            <Toolbar visible="{= ${cart>/itemCount} > 0}">

                <!--
                [INTERMEDIATE] TOTAL PRICE DISPLAY
                ====================================================
                ObjectNumber is used for a nicely formatted price display.

                number="{cart>/totalPrice}"
                  Bound to the totalPrice property of the cart model.
                  This value is maintained by the cart.js module,
                  which recalculates it whenever items are added/removed.

                unit="{cart>/currency}"
                  Currency from the cart model (e.g., "USD").

                emphasized="true"
                  [INTERMEDIATE] Makes the number stand out with bolder
                  styling. Use for the most important numeric value
                  on the page (in this case, the total price).

                [ADVANCED] ALTERNATIVE: Using formatPrice FORMATTER
                You could also format the price with a formatter:
                  number="{
                    path: 'cart>/totalPrice',
                    formatter: '.formatter.formatPrice'
                  }"
                But since ObjectNumber already handles number formatting,
                we keep it simple and let the control do the formatting.
                -->
                <Title
                    text="{i18n>total}:"
                    level="H4"
                />
                <ObjectNumber
                    number="{
                        path: 'cart>/totalPrice',
                        formatter: '.formatter.formatPrice'
                    }"
                    unit="{cart>/currency}"
                    emphasized="true"
                />

                <ToolbarSpacer />

                <!--
                [BEGINNER] PROCEED TO CHECKOUT BUTTON
                ====================================================
                press=".onProceedToCheckout"
                  The controller navigates to the "checkout" route:
                    this.getRouter().navTo("checkout");

                type="Emphasized"
                  Primary action — visually prominent.

                icon="sap-icon://cart"
                  Cart icon reinforces the action's context.

                [BEST PRACTICE] SINGLE PRIMARY ACTION
                There's only ONE emphasized button in the footer.
                Fiori guidelines say each page should have at most
                one primary (emphasized) action to guide the user.
                -->
                <Button
                    text="{i18n>proceedToCheckout}"
                    type="Emphasized"
                    icon="sap-icon://cart"
                    press=".onProceedToCheckout"
                />
            </Toolbar>
        </footer>

    </Page>

</mvc:View>
